'''Mirza Muhammad Siraj ud-Daulah''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|میرزا محمد سراج الدولہ}}}}, [[Bengali language|Bengali]]: '''নবাব সিরাজদৌল্লা'''), more commonly known as ''Siraj ud-Daulah'' (1733 &ndash; July 2, 1757), was the last independent [[Nawab of Bengal]]. The end of his reign marked the start of [[British East India Company]] rule over Bengal and later almost all of [[South Asia]]. He was sometimes called, and his name rendered, "''Sir Roger Dowler''" or "''Sir Roger Dowlah''" by some of his British contemporaries, and "''Sau Raja Dowla''" by [[John Zephaniah Holwell|John Holwell]]. However these distorted early English renderings, among others like "''Sepoy''", were rebuked and ridiculed by later writers.

